Analyze the following PlantUML use case model and detect if it contains any antipatterns.
Base your analysis solely on the model provided. Do not use any outside knowledge.


PlantUML Model:
@startuml
' Version 1 – contains Functional Decomposition: Using the include relationship

actor "Applicant" as Applicant
actor "Passport Officer" as Officer

rectangle "Passport Application System" {
  usecase "Submit Passport Application" as UC1
  usecase "Upload Photo" as UC2
  usecase "Check Application Status" as UC3
  usecase "Review Application" as UC4
  usecase "Schedule Appointment" as UC5
  usecase "Issue Passport" as UC6
  usecase "Reject Application" as UC7
}

Applicant --> UC1
UC1 ..> UC2 : <<include>>
Applicant --> UC3
Applicant --> UC5
Officer --> UC4
Officer --> UC6
UC6 ..> UC4 : <<include>>
UC4 ..> UC7 : <<extend>>

@enduml


Answer:
Antipattern Detected: Functional Decomposition: Using the include relationship

   Constructs Involved: Submit Passport Application, Upload Photo
   Explanation: The use case "Upload Photo" is an inclusion use case that is included by only one use case ("Submit Passport Application"). "Upload Photo" is not associated with any actor directly — no actor has a direct association to it. It does not include or extend any other use case, is not extended by any use case, and is neither a generalization nor a specialization of any use case. "Upload Photo" represents a sub-step of the application submission process rather than a complete, standalone service offering an observable result to a user. This is a textbook instance of Functional Decomposition via the include relationship, where a single use case has been improperly broken down into a sub-function that has no independent value to any actor.
